Recently, cyber attacks on the business world have become more frequent.
Access to data from companies such as JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target caused them losses of hundreds of millions, and in some cases even billions of dollars.
Doing damage to the global economy does not require too many such attacks.
Nor is the public sector immune to such problems.
Between 2012 and 2014, there was a significant data leak at the U.S. Office of Human Resources Management.
Access to data on security checks and fingerprints of 22 million employees was compromised.
Attempts by state-sponsored hackers to influence election results in a number of countries using stolen data are known.
The last two high-volume disclosures concern the Bundestag, Germany's federal parliament, and the theft of Democratic National Committee emails.
The cyber threat affects our democratic processes.
The situation is even getting worse.
As computer technology develops, data protection systems become increasingly vulnerable.
A new type of computer technology, computing on quantum computers, which use the microscopic properties of nature to dramatically increase computing power, is also a cause for concern.
It is so powerful that it will be able to crack many modern encryption systems.
Is the situation so hopeless?
Maybe it's time to pack our vital data and prepare for the imminent digital apocalypse?
I would say, "It's not time yet."
Quantum computers are still in development, and it will take many years before they are put into practice.
More importantly, there are major breakthroughs in encryption.
For me, this is a particularly exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned about the new possibility of creating quantum effects that do not exist in nature, I was very excited.
I was intrigued by the idea of applying the fundamental laws of physics to create more secure encryption.
Today, a number of companies and laboratories around the world, including mine, are working on these technologies to put them into practice.
Right.
Now we are preparing to fight quantum with quantum.
So how does it all work?
First, let's take a small dive into the world of encryption.
To do this, we will need a briefcase, some important documents that we want to send to our friend, James Bond, and a lock to keep everything safe.
Since our information is top secret, we need a special portfolio.
It has a special code lock: when closed, it converts all text in documents into random numbers.
You put the documents in a briefcase, close the lock - at which point all the documents are converted into random numbers - and send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on the way, you call James to report the code.
After receiving the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decrypted, and voila - you just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A funny example, but it illustrates three important coding elements.
Code - we call it the "encryption key."
It's like a password.
Call James to tell him the lock combination code.
This is called "key exchange" -
a guarantee that you will securely receive the encryption key from the right place.
And a lock that encodes and decodes the document.
This is called a "coding algorithm."
Using a key, it converts text in documents into random numbers.
A good algorithm will encode in such a way that it is very difficult to decrypt a document without a key.
The importance of encryption is that if someone takes possession of a portfolio and hacks it without the help of an encryption key and an encoding algorithm, they still won't be able to read its contents.
The information will look like a set of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure way of exchanging keys to transfer the encryption key to the right place.
However, the rapid development of computing power threatens a number of modern methods of key exchange.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today - RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was estimated that it would take 40 quadrillion years to crack the 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was hacked.
As computers became more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
Today we usually use 2,048 or 4,096 bits.
As you can see, code creators and hackers are engaged in an ongoing battle, trying to outwit each other.
And when quantum computers appear in the next 10-15 years, they will be able to crack even faster the complex mathematics that underlies many modern encryption systems.
A quantum computer is likely to turn our current secure fortress into a simple house of cards.
We must find a way to protect our fortress.
In recent years, the number of studies in the field of using quantum effects to strengthen crypto protection has been increasing.
Some interesting discoveries have been made.
Remember the three main elements of encryption: high quality keys, secure key exchange, and a sophisticated algorithm?
Advances in science and technology threaten two of these three elements.
First, the keys themselves.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But to date, they are not entirely random.
Today, we create encryption keys from sequences of random numbers generated from software, so-called pseudo-random numbers.
In the numbers generated by the program or mathematical formula, one way or another, there is a certain regularity.
The less random the numbers are - in scientific terms: the less entropy they contain - the easier it is to predict them.
Recently, several casinos have been the victims of an ingenious attack.
Combinations at the output of slot machines were recorded for some time, after which they were analyzed.
This allowed cybercriminals to redesign the pseudo-random number generator that controls the drums.
This, in turn, made it possible to predict the spins of the reels with high accuracy and get a big win.
Encryption keys can also be exposed to similar risks.
A truly random number generator is needed for secure encryption.
For many years, scientists have been looking for the possibility of creating such a generator.
But most attempts today are either not random enough, not fast enough, or difficult to repeat.
But the quantum world is based on chance.
Therefore, it makes sense to take advantage of this fact.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can also create an infinite stream of random numbers at high speeds -
which will prevent all these potential criminals from entering the casinos.
A number of top universities and companies around the world are developing truly random number generators.
The first quantum generator created in my company was one by two meters in size and was placed on an optical table.
Later, we were able to reduce it to the size of a server box.
Today it is the size of a PCI card connected to a standard computer.
It is the world's fastest generator of truly random numbers.
Its performance is a billion random numbers per second.
Today, it is used to strengthen the security system by cloud providers, banks, and government agencies around the world.
(Applause) But even with such a generator, the second big problem remains unresolved: the threat to secure key exchange.
Modern methods of key exchange are not compatible with a quantum computer.
The quantum solution to this problem is called "quantum key distribution" or QKD, which is based on the fundamental, paradoxical characteristic of quantum mechanics.
The quantum particle changes depending on its observation.
Let me give you an example of how this works.
Let's get back to exchanging lockdown codes with James Bond.
Only this time, instead of calling James with a code message, we will use quantum effects on the laser to create the code and send it to James using normal optical fibre.
We believe that Dr. Nou will try to hack access to data exchange.
Fortunately, his attempts to catch quantum keys en route will leave fingerprints that James and you will be able to detect.
This will make it possible to exclude intercepted keys.
And the remaining keys can be used for enhanced data protection.
Since such security is based on the fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer, or even any supercomputer of the future, will not be able to hack it.
My team and I are working with leading universities, as well as the defence sector, to develop this promising technology into next-generation security tools.
The Internet of Things heralds an era in which 25-30 billion devices are expected to interact by 2020.
For the proper functioning of our society in the world of the Internet of Things, trust in the systems that support these devices is vital.
I am ready to bet that quantum technologies will be able to provide this trust, allowing us to take full advantage of the amazing innovations that will enrich our lives.
Thank you.
(Applause)
