One winter morning a few years ago, I was driving to work in Johannesburg, South Africa, and noticed fog hanging over the city.
I drive there almost every day, so it's unlikely I wouldn't have paid attention earlier.
Johannesburg is known for its special skyline, which I could barely see that morning.
Soon I realised it was a huge cloud of polluted air.
The contrast between my usual picturesque environment and that smog-shrouded sky stirred up something in me.
I was horrified that this city of colourful and picturesque sunsets would be engulfed in darkness.
At that moment, I had a strong desire to do something, but I didn't know what.
All I knew was that I couldn't stay away.
The main difficulty was that I didn't really understand ecology, air quality management or atmospheric chemistry.
I'm a computer engineer and I was sure I couldn't handle the problem with code.
(Laughter) Who am I to make a difference?
But I was a resident of this city.
In the years that followed, I learned one very important lesson - one that needs to be taken seriously if we are to have a better future.
Even if you are not an expert in any field, your experience from outside can be the key to solving complex problems in this area.
Sometimes your unique vision can result in an extraordinary idea that will move everything from the dead end, but you have to be bold enough to try it.
This is the only way out.
Even then, I realised that in order to at least try to make a difference, first I would have to sort out air pollution, so I became a student again.
Already at the very beginning of my research, I learned that air pollution is the greatest danger to the environment.
According to the World Health Organization, nearly 14 percent of global deaths in 2012 were caused by air pollution in homes and ambient air pollution, which is especially common in low- and middle-income countries.
Air pollution alone causes more deaths each year than malaria or HIV/AIDS.
In Africa, the number of premature deaths due to unsafe sanitation or child malnutrition is no match for the number of deaths due to air pollution, and it costs huge economic costs: more than $400 billion as of 2013, according to a study by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
Now, in my work, I am exploring new opportunities in the field of artificial intelligence, where the symbiotic relationship between man and machine will help find a favorable basis for making the right decisions.
In the process of studying the problem of air pollution, it became clear that we need to find a way to make better decisions to control air pollution, and given the scale of the problem, it is necessary to do this together.
So I decided to get to know people who work in this area.
I started meeting with officials from Johannesburg and other nearby cities, I also engaged the local scientific community and also made some cold calls.
The networking process I took up helped me gain a deeper understanding of the problem.
It also helped me avoid falling into the trap that my colleagues often fall into when trying to innovate, when we quickly apply technology before we are clearly aware of the problem.
I started to think about what I could do to improve the situation.
I just started asking myself how I could effectively combine all my programming and artificial intelligence skills with the experiences of the people I met.
I wanted to create an online platform for air quality regulation that would identify patterns in pollution, look to the future and determine what we should expect.
I was determined to put my idea into practice, but faced uncertainty, I had no guarantee of success.
I only had a certain set of engineering skills, skills that I had acquired in my profession (Laughter) and that people dealing with air pollution had not had for years.
I realized that sometimes just one fresh look, some new skills create the conditions for the appearance of something outstanding.
Will power and imagination are our guiding star, empowering us to find new ways and circumvent difficulties.
Armed with a deep understanding of the problem of air pollution and having studied decades of information on pollutant concentrations and meteorological conditions in Johannesburg and beyond, my colleagues from South Africa and China and I have created an air decision support system that is in the cloud.
The software system analyzes historical data and data in real time to identify spatial and temporal trends.
We then used new machine learning technology to predict pollution levels for different pollutants a few days in advance.
This means that residents can make better decisions about their movements and choice of place of residence for their families.
We will be able to predict pollution cases in advance, calculate the culprits of pollution, who, by order of the authorities, will be forced to reduce the scale of their activities.
With the help of scenario planning, urban planners will be able to make the right decisions in the development of infrastructure, such as residential settlements, industrial zones.
We completed testing of our technology, which lasted about 120 days, covering the whole of South Africa.
The results were approved when we demonstrated a close relationship between the forecast data and the data we received on the spot.
Thanks to our leadership, we have created cutting-edge, innovative technologies that will be able to predict air quality with unprecedented accuracy, improving a city that not so long ago I drove one winter morning and thought: "Something is wrong here. What can be done?"
And here's my conclusion: what if I hadn't studied air pollution then?
What if I hadn't expressed concern about the state of the environment and just hoped that someone somewhere was already dealing with the problem?
That's what I've learned: when we decide on a complex enterprise that contributes to what we firmly believe in, it's important to focus on success and consider the consequences of inaction.
We must not get out of the way in the face of obstacles and difficulties, this should motivate us even more.
Wherever you are, when you realise that your natural curiosity is aroused by something and it's something that excites you and you have crazy and bold ideas and maybe it's beyond your competence, ask yourself: why not?
Why not take action and solve the problem in your own way, as you can?
And perhaps you will be pleasantly surprised.
Thank you.
(Applause)
