I thought about the evolution of technology that led me to where I was then - how the first colour photographs were calibrated to the skin of white women, meaning colour photographs were not adapted to dark faces.
And this is the same prejudice, the same gap was observed in the 90s.
And the same information gap we have today is how well we can recognise diverse human faces with facial recognition technology.
I was thinking about the latest research, where we tend to limit our thinking to one set of data and one problem.
And by doing so, we created more gaps and prejudices that AI could develop even more.
I realised that we need to think more about how the technologies we are working with today will look in 5 and 10 years.
Mankind evolves slowly, correcting problems in the interaction between people and the environment over time.
Artificial intelligence, by contrast, is evolving at an incredible rate.
