Today I would like to show you how we will do different things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and cars will be self-assembling, reproducing and repairing themselves.
So, I'm going to show you what I consider to be the current stage of industrial development, and then compare it with some natural systems.
So, at the current stage of industrial development, we have skyscrapers - 2.5 years, from 500,000 to a million parts, quite complex, new amazing technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have amazing machines that can take us into space - 5 years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if we look at natural systems, we see proteins of two million species that can gather in 10,000 nanoseconds, or a chain of DNA with three billion basic pairs that we can copy in about an hour.
So, natural systems, for all their complexity, are extremely efficient, far more effective than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They are much more energy efficient.
They are almost never wrong.
And they can rebuild themselves over a long life.
So, there is something very interesting about natural systems.
And if we can bring that into our man-made environment, our way of creating things will have tremendous potential.
And I think the key is self-assembly.
So, if we want to use self-assembly in our physical environment, I think four key factors need to be considered.
First, we need to decipher the complexity of what we want to build - our buildings and cars.
And it is necessary to decompose them into a simple sequence - the basic DNA of construction processes.
Then we will need programmable parts that can understand this sequence and use it to curl up or reassemble.
We will need a certain amount of energy that will make it possible to activate all this, make the parts capable of gathering according to the program.
And we need some kind of backup bug fixing system to ensure the successful construction of what we want.
I'm going to show you some of the projects that EmIT and I are working on to achieve this self-fulfilling future.
The first two are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These are projects - large-scale reconfigurable robots - 2.5 and 3.5 meter squirrels.
Mechanical electrical devices and sensors are built into them.
You paint what you need to curl into, into a sequence of angles - minus 120, minus 120, 0, 0, 120, minus 120 - something like that; a sequence of angles or turns, and you send that sequence along the cord.
Each block receives its own message - minus 120. It turns this corner, checks if everything is correct and transmits information to a neighbor.
And these are brilliant scientists, engineers, designers who worked on this project.
And I think it really raises the question: are other scales possible here?
I mean, thousands of dollars, lots of man-hours to make this 2.5 meter robot.
Can we really scale up? Can we really embed robotics in every part?
The next project solves this issue, considers the passive character, or tries to get modified programmability passively.
But he goes one step further and tries to get a real calculation.
Basically, it has the most fundamental building block of calculations, the logical element of the digital integrated circuit directly in each part.
This is the "I-NOT" element.
You have one tetrahedron - an element that will do all the calculations, and two tetrahedrons to enter.
One for user input, it's the way you put the bricks.
Another for information from the previous brick laid.
And then it displays information in three-dimensional space.
So, this means that the user can start moving the bricks in the right direction.
His calculations are based on what was done before and what you told him to do.
And now it starts to move in three-dimensional space - up or down.
On the left side, [1.1] the input equals 0 at the output, moving down.
On the right side, [0.0] the input is 1 at the output, which means moving upwards.
And what really matters is that our structures now contain blueprints of what we want to build.
They contain all the information about what was built.
So, it means that we have some form of self-reproduction.
In this case, I call it self-directed reproduction because the structures contain clear drawings.
If there are errors, you can replace the part.
All local information is stored so you know how to fix it.
So you may have something that moves and reads information and can transfer it from one part to another.
It is built directly inside, without external control.
The last project I will show you is called Displaced Chains, and this is perhaps the most exciting example of what we now have of passive self-assembling systems.
It combines the ability to reconfigure and program and creates a completely passive system.
At the core, we have a chain of elements.
All elements are completely identical, and displaced.
So every chain or every element wants to turn right or left.
And when you assemble a chain, you essentially program it.
You tell each block where it should turn: right or left.
So when you shake the chain, it rolls into the configuration you have programmed - in this case a spiral, or in this case two cubes next to each other.
So in general, you can program any three-dimensional form - or one-dimensional, two-dimensional - of these completely passive circuits.
So, what does this tell us about the future?
I think this tells us that there are new opportunities for self-assembly, replication, and repair in our physical structures, buildings, and machines.
New software is possible in these parts.
And from here, you have new opportunities in computing.
We will have space computers.
Imagine our buildings, bridges, cars, all our bricks could do the calculations.
This is an amazing parallel and distributed cleaning force, new design possibilities.
This is an incredible potential.
I think the projects I have shown you are only a small step towards the future, if we introduce these new technologies, towards a new self-assembled future.
Thank you.
