It is believed that only sighted people can drive a car.
Until recently, it was believed that for a blind person, safe and independent driving is an impossible task.
Hello, I am Dennis Hong, and we give the blind freedom and independence by developing a car for the visually impaired.
Before talking about this car for the blind, I will briefly talk about another project I worked on, called the DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses "start," and without his participation the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, taking third place in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NFU, tasked the research committee with developing a vehicle that can independently and safely drive a blind person.
We decided to try our hand because we thought, "Hey, what's difficult about that?
We already have an autonomous car.
Put a blind man in it - and it's over, isn't it? "
(Laughter) But we were deeply mistaken.
The NFU wanted not just a car that would transport the blind, but a car that the blind could drive themselves.
So we had to reject everything and start from scratch.
So, to test this crazy idea, we developed a small car buggy prototype to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited blind youth from all over the country and gave them the opportunity to test this car.
It was an amazing experience.
But the catch is that this car was designed to operate in a strictly controlled environment, namely in a flat, closed parking lot, where even lanes are limited by red signal cones.
Due to this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So, how does it work?
Well, it's a pretty complex system, but let me clarify, perhaps even simplify it.
So, it has three components.
These are tactile perception, computation and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver sees nothing, the system must perceive the environment and collect information for the driver.
For this purpose, an initial parameter meter is used.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, like a person's inner ear.
This information is then transmitted to a GPS device to assess the location of the vehicle.
Two cameras are used to detect lanes on the road
and three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the space around the car to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or overtaking car, any obstacles encountered on the road or around the car.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer, and the computer performs two stages.
First of all, it is processing this information to get an idea of space: determining lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then bringing this information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to figure out the safest way to drive a car.
So, we can also give advice on how to operate the machine.
But the problem is how to convey this information and instructions to a blind person who does not have the fast and accurate reaction necessary to drive?
For this purpose, we have developed a number of interface technologies for the blind:
A three-dimensional ping sound system, a vibrating vest, a rudder with sound signals, a special prosthetic leg, and even shoes that put pressure on the leg.
But today we will only talk about three types of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
This is a pair of gloves with motors on the joints of the fingers, instructing the driver how to steer: direction and angle of turn.
Another device is the SpeedStrip.
It was originally a massage chair.
The vibration is used to transmit speed information to the driver, as well as to guide the use of gas and brake pedals.
So, here you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. And since the vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is sensory data, it is transmitted to devices via a computer.
The DriveGrip and SpeedStrip devices are very effective.
But the problem is that these are teaching aids.
They don't actually give freedom to govern, do they?
The on-board computer gives the driver commands: "left," "right," "speed up," "stop."
We call him an "annoying passenger from the back seat."
Therefore, we are moving away from educational prompting devices and focusing on informative devices.
An excellent example of such an interface is AirPix.
This is a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many holes through which compressed air exits, thereby creating images.
A blind person can bring his palm to this panel and "see" lanes on the roadway and obstacles.
The driver can also change the frequency at which the air is released and possibly the temperature of the air.
That is, it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So, here you see the left and right camera of the car, and how the computer processes and sends this information to the AirPix panel.
Here we demonstrate a simulator, a blind person drives a car using AirPix.
This simulator proved to be very useful for training blind drivers, as well as for quickly testing ideas for using different types of special interfaces.
That's how this system works in a nutshell.
After all, this is a prototype car for the blind. And it will not be released on the roadway until they are convinced of its absolute safety.
And I sincerely believe that this is quite likely.
Still, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will the rules of auto insurance change?
On what conditions will a driver's license be issued?
Beyond the technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls that need to be overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main goal of this project is to develop a car for the blind.
However, it is possible that the spin-off technologies developed during this project will prove to be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of the time of day, fog and rain.
We can use these technologies together with new special interfaces to improve the safety of visually impaired vehicles.
Or for the blind. Find their use in everyday household appliances, in educational institutions, in offices.
Just imagine: a teacher in the classroom writes on a blackboard, and a blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
It's priceless.
So what I showed you today is just the beginning.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
